<h1>Color usage</h1>
<p>Color is a core element of the Vivid:Apps design system. This guide outlines the principles, patterns, and token structure that define how color is applied across components and experiences.</p>

{{ heading('Overview', '2') }}
{{ heading('Color modes', '3') }}
<p>Vivid:Apps offers two color modes, <b>light</b> and <b>dark</b>. Every pattern in Vivid:Apps is built to work across both color modes out of the box.</p>

{{ heading('Color design tokens', '3') }}
<p>Vivid:Apps provides color through design tokens - a layer of abstraction that enables consistency, maintainability, and theming across the system. In code, these tokens are exposed as CSS variables, while in Figma they are represented as variables.</p>
<p>For example, when using a token such as <code>color-surface-default</code> for a background, its value will automatically adapt based on the active colour mode.</p>

{{ heading('Design token groups', '3') }}
<p>Vivid:Apps design tokens are categorized into three groups:</p>

