{{ heading('Alpha colors', '4') }}
<p>Alpha colors have varying levels of transparency or opacity (80%, 85%, 90%) and are available for all core colors. They are useful for creating layered visual effects, such as overlays and hover states, and help UI adapt to different background colors and elevations.</p>
{{ colorScaleExample(tokens.color.primary, colorScale, scaleItem, 0, 0, '', true ) }}

{{ heading('Neutral colors', '3') }}
<p>Neutral colors apply to most surface backgrounds, text, and shapes in our interfaces. They don't typically have a meaning associated with them, though they can imply things like disabled states.</p>
{{ heading('Backgrounds', '4') }}
<p>The first few steps are typically used for surafce and canvas background colours. The most commonly used are <code>color-bg-surface-default</code>  and <code>color-bg-surface-muted</code>.</p>
<p>Text and border contrast is measured against <code>color-surface-muted</code>, ensuring consistent and accessible contrast ratios across both muted and default backgrounds.</p>
{{ colorScaleExample(tokens.color.neutral, colorScale, scaleItem, 0, 3, 'Backgrounds' ) }}

{{ heading('Borders & dividers', '4') }}
<p>The next steps (4 to 6 on the neutral scale and 3 to 5 on other scales) are typically used for borders and dividers.</p>
{{ colorScaleExample(tokens.color.neutral, colorScale, scaleItem, 4, 6, 'Borders' ) }}

{{ heading('Text & icons', '4') }}
<p>The next steps (7 to 12 on the neutral scale and 6 to 10 on other scales) are typically used for text and icons.</p>
{{ colorScaleExample(tokens.color.neutral, colorScale, scaleItem, 7, 11, 'Text & icons' ) }}

